nts [[Maximian]] ([[Marcus Aurelius Valerius Maximianus Herculius]]) co-emperor, splitting the '''[[Roman Empire]]''' into a [[dyarchy]] with capitals at [[Mediolanum]] (now [[Milan, Italy]]) and [[Augusta Treverorum]] (now [[Trier, Germany]]).\n|-\n|align=center|274||||[[Roman Empire|Roman Emperor]] [[Aurelian]] conquers the '''[[Palmyrene Empire]]''' which is subsumed back into the '''[[Roman Empire]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|273||||[[Roman Empire|Roman Emperor]] [[Aurelian]] ([[Lucius Domitius Aurelianus]]) conquers the '''[[Gallic Empire]]''' which is subsumed back into the '''[[Roman Empire]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|271||||Roman Dacia is abandoned\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|269||||The '''[[Palmyrene Empire]]''' conquers the '''[[Roman Empire|Roman Province]] of [[Egypt]]'''.\n|-\n|||Roman Emperor [[Claudius Gothicus|Claudius II]] recovers Hispania from the Gallic Empire\n|-\n|align=center|266||||[[Emperor Wu of Jin|Wu]] establishes the '''[[Jin dynasty (266\u2013420)|Western Jin dynasty]]''' in '''[[China]]'''. [[Luoyang]] and [[Chang'an]] are the capitals.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|260||||[[Syria|Syrian Queen]] [[Zenobia]] breaks from the '''[[Roman Empire]]''' and establishes the '''[[Palmyrene Empire]]'''. [[Palmyra]] is the capital.\n|-\n|||[[Postumus]] ([[Marcus Cassianius Latinius Postumus]]) breaks from the '''[[Roman Empire]]''' and establishes the '''[[Gallic Empire]]'''. [[Colonia Agrippina]] (now [[Cologne, Germany]]) is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|240||||[[Gupta Empire]] forms in India\n|-\n|align=center|222||||[[Sun Quan|Da]] establishes '''[[Eastern Wu]]''' in '''[[China]]'''. [[Ezhou|Wuchang]] and [[Jiankang|Jianye]] are the capitals.\n|-\n|align=center|221||||[[Liu Bei|Zhaolie]] establishes '''[[Shu Han]]''' in '''[[China]]'''. [[Chengdu]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|220||||[[Cao Pi|Wen]] establishes '''[[Cao Wei]]''' in '''[[China]]'''. [[Xuchang]] and [[Luoyang]] are the capitals.\n|}\n\n===1st century===\n[[File:BlankMap-World-1ce.png|thumb|right|World in year 1.]]\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:10%\"|Year||style=\"width:8%\"|Date||style=\"width:82%\"|Event\n|-\n|align=center|[[3 CE]]||||The '''[[Goguryeo]]''' of [[Korea]] moves its capital from [[Jolbon]] to [[Gungnae-seong|Gungnae]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[5 CE]]||||Romans conquer much of the [[Middle East]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[9 CE]]||||[[Wang Mang]] establishes the '''[[Xin dynasty]]''' in '''[[China]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|[[25 CE]]||||[[Emperor Guangwu of Han|Guangwu]] establishes the '''[[Han dynasty#Eastern Han|Eastern Han dynasty]]''' in '''[[China]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|[[40 CE]]||||The '''[[Tr\u01b0ng Sisters]]''' rebel against [[First Chinese domination of Vietnam|Chinese rule]] in '''[[Vietnam]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|[[43 CE]]||||Start of the [[Second Chinese domination of Vietnam]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[43 CE|43]]-[[47 CE]]||||The [[Roman Empire|Romans]] found [[Roman London|Londinium]], a town that will with time become modern London\n|-\n|align=center|[[71 CE|71]]-[[84 CE]]||||Conquest of [[Wales]] and [[Scotland]] by Romans\n|}\n\n==Before the Common Era==\n\n===First Millennium BCE===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:8%\"|Year||style=\"width:8%\"|Date||style=\"width:84%\"|Event\n|-\n|align=center|[[18&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Onjo of Baekje|Onjo]] establishes '''[[Baekje]]''' on the central [[Korean Peninsula]]. [[Wiryeseong]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[27&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|16&nbsp;January||The [[Roman Senate]] grants [[Gaius Julius Caesar Octavianus]] the title [[Augustus (honorific)|Augustus]]. This effectively ends the [[Roman Republic]] and establishes the '''[[Roman Empire]]'''. The city of [[Rome]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[30&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|1&nbsp;August||[[Roman Republic|Roman]] [[consul]] [[Gaius Julius Caesar Octavianus]] conquers the '''[[Ptolemaic Dynasty of Egypt|Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt]]'''. Octavianus organizes [[Egypt]] as a province under his personal control.\n|-\n|align=center|35&nbsp;BCE||||The [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] conquer the city of [[Sirmium]], modern [[Sremska Mitrovica]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[37&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[King Dongmyeong of Goguryeo|Dongmyeong]] establishes '''[[Goguryeo]]''' on the northern [[Korean Peninsula]]. [[Jolbon]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[58&nbsp;BCE|58]]-[[50&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer [[Gaul]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[57&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Hyeokgeose of Silla|Hyeokgeose]] establishes '''[[Silla]]''' on the southeast [[Korean Peninsula]]. [[Gyeongju]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[63&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer [[Jerusalem]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[63&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans annex western [[Kingdom of Pontus|Pontus]] and create a client state out of the Eastern portion under [[Pharnaces II of Pontus|Pharnaces II]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[111&nbsp;BCE]]||||By this date, the [[Han dynasty]] under [[Emperor Wu of Han|Wu]] had conquered much of what is today Southern China and Northern Vietnam from [[Nanyue]]. Start of the [[First Chinese domination of Vietnam]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[133&nbsp;BCE]]||||Upon the death of [[Attalus III]], he wills his kingdom of [[Pergamon]] to the [[Roman Republic]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[133&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer Celtiberia following the Siege of Numantia\n|-\n|align=center|[[135&nbsp;BCE]]||||Western half of [[Minyue]] conquered by the [[Han dynasty]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberia]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Ancient Carthage]] is disestablished\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer [[Corinth]] and dissolve the [[Achaean League]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||Roman provinces of [[Macedonia (Roman province)|Macedon]] and [[Achaea (Roman province)|Achaea]] formed\n|-\n|align=center|[[148&nbsp;BCE]]||||Mithridates I of Parthia conquers Ectebana\n|-\n|align=center|[[168&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans dissolve the Kingdom of Macedon after the Battle of Pydna.\n|-\n|align=center|[[180&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Demetrius I of Bactria]] invades India, forming the [[Indo-Greek Kingdom]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[187&nbsp;BCE]]||||The [[Shunga Empire]] is formed after the [[Mauryan Empire]] is destroyed\n|-\n|align=center|[[194&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Wanggeom-seong]] becomes the capital of '''[[Wiman Joseon]]''' on the [[Korean Peninsula]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[194&nbsp;BCE]]||||Seleucids take control of Coele Syria and Judea from Ptolemaic Egypt\n|-\n|align=center|[[194&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans force Philip of Macedon to abandon Greece in the Peace of Flamininus, while allowing him to maintain Macedon itself.\n|-\n|align=center|[[202&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|28&nbsp;February||[[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Gaozu]] establishes the '''[[Han dynasty#Western Han|Western Han dynasty]] in [[China]]'''. [[Chang'an]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[204&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Zhao Tuo|Wu]] establishes '''[[Nanyue]]''' in what is now Southern China. [[Panyu District|Panyu]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[209&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||The Romans conquer Cartagena from the Carthaginians, bringing Carthaginian Spain under Roman control\n|-\n|align=center|[[211&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||Romans capture [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[221&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Qin Shi Huang]] unifies [[History of China#Qin dynasty (221-206 BCE)|ancient China]] and establishes the '''[[Qin dynasty]] in [[China]]'''. [[Xianyang]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[230&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Han (state)|Han]] conquered by [[Qin (state)|Qin]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[238&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Arsaces I of Parthia]] establishes the '''[[Arsacid Dynasty of Parthia]]'''. [[Hecatompylus]] becomes the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[238&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Sardinia]] and [[Corsica]] become Roman provinces\n|-\n|align=center|[[238&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Sicily]] becomes first Roman province\n|-\n|align=center|[[266&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Ashoka]] unifies most of South Asia\n|-\n|align=center|[[281&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Lysimachus]] dies at the [[Battle of Corupedium]], his empire falling to the [[Seleucid Empire|Seleucids]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[291&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius Poliorcetes]] captures Thebes after a successful [[Siege of Thebes (292\u2013291 BC)|siege]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[294&nbsp;BCE]]||||Demetrius I of Macedon kills [[Alexander V of Macedon]], and in claiming the throne loses [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]] to a revolt.\n|-\n|align=center|[[301&nbsp;BCE]]||||The death of [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus]] at the [[Battle of Ipsus]] results in his kingdom being divided between the remaining [[Diadochi]], namely [[Ptolemy I Soter]], [[Seleucus I Nicator]], [[Lysimachus]], and [[Cassander]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[305&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Macedon]]ian general [[Ptolemy I Soter|Ptolemy]] establishes the '''[[Ptolemaic Dynasty of Egypt]]''' as King [[Ptolemy I Soter]]. [[Alexandria]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[306&nbsp;BCE]]||||Following the death of [[Alexander IV of Macedon]], [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus]] declares himself an independent king, soon to by followed by his fellow Diadochi [[Ptolemy I Soter]], [[Seleucus I Nicator]], [[Lysimachus]], and [[Cassander]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[309&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Seleucus I Nicator]] forms the [[Seleucid Empire]] after conquering Babylonia, Media, and Elam from [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus]] in the [[Babylonian War]], leaving him with one third of his empire.\n|-\n|align=center|[[312&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Macedon]]ian general [[Seleucus I Nicator|Seleucus]] establishes the '''[[Seleucid Empire]]'''. [[Babylon]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[316&nbsp;BCE]]||||The states of [[Shu (state)|Shu]] and [[Ba (state)|Ba]] are conquered by [[King Huiwen of Qin]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[322&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Chandragupta Maurya|Chandragupta]] establishes the '''[[Maurya Empire]]''' of [[History of India#Maurya dynasty|ancient India]]. [