ter|about&nbsp;2070&nbsp;BCE||[[Yu the Great]] establishes the '''[[Xia dynasty]]''' in '''[[China]]'''. [[Yangcheng (historical city)|Yangcheng]] and [[Zhenxun]] are the capitals.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2112&nbsp;BCE||[[Utu-hengal]] defeats the [[Gutian people|Gutians]] and establishes the '''[[Third Dynasty of Ur]]'''.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|about&nbsp;2130&nbsp;BCE||[[Mentuhotep I]] establishes the '''[[Eleventh Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] becomes the capital of '''[[Upper Egypt]]'''.\n|-\n|[[Meryhathor]] establishes the '''[[Tenth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Herakleopolis Magna|Henen-nesut]] remains the capital of '''[[Lower Egypt]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2160&nbsp;BCE||[[Meryibre Khety]] establishes the '''[[Ninth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Herakleopolis Magna|Henen-nesut]] becomes the capital of '''[[Lower Egypt]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2165&nbsp;BCE||[[Neferkare Pepiseneb]] establishes the '''[[Eighth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2175&nbsp;BCE||[[Netjerkare]] establishes the '''[[Seventh Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2181&nbsp;BCE||The '''[[Old Kingdom of Egypt]]''' collapses, beginning the '''[[First Intermediate Period of Egypt]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2193&nbsp;BCE|| The '''[[Akkadian Empire]]''' collapses after an invasion by the '''[[Gutians|Gutian people]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2270&nbsp;BCE||[[Sargon of Akkad]] establishes the '''[[Sumer]]ian [[Akkadian Empire|First Dynasty of Akkad]]''' after defeating [[Lugal-zage-si]] at the [[Battle of Uruk]]. [[Akkad (city)|Akkad]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2333&nbsp;BCE||[[Dangun Wanggeom]] establishes '''[[Gojoseon]]''' on the [[Korean Peninsula]].\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2380&nbsp;BCE||[[Ur-Nanshe]] establishes the '''[[Sumer]]ian [[Lagash|First Dynasty of Lagash]]'''. [[Lagash]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2336&nbsp;BCE||[[Teti]] establishes the '''[[Sixth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2494&nbsp;BCE||[[Userkaf]] establishes the '''[[Fifth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2580&nbsp;BCE||[[Mesannepada]] establishes the '''[[Sumerian king list#First dynasty of Ur|First Dynasty of Ur]]'''. [[Ur]] becomes the [[de facto]] capital of '''[[Sumer]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2655&nbsp;BCE||[[Sneferu]] establishes the '''[[Fourth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2686&nbsp;BCE||The '''[[Old Kingdom of Egypt]]''' is established. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] remains the capital. This era sees the building of the [[Egyptian pyramids]].\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2727&nbsp;BCE||[[Djoser]] establishes the '''[[Third Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] becomes the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2860&nbsp;BCE||[[Hotepsekhemwy]] establishes the '''[[Second Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;2879&nbsp;BCE||[[Kinh D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng|D\u01b0\u01a1ng V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] establishes the '''[[H\u1ed3ng B\u00e0ng dynasty]]''' in '''[[Vietnam]]'''.\n|}\n\n===Fourth Millennium BCE===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:5%\"|Year||style=\"width:95%\"|Event\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;3080&nbsp;BCE||[[Narmer]] (or [[Menes]]) unites '''[[Lower Egypt]]''' and '''[[Upper Egypt]]''' under the '''[[First Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] becomes the capital of all [[Ancient Egypt|Egypt]].\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |about&nbsp;3200&nbsp;BCE||The regional power centers of '''[[Thinis]]''', '''[[Naqada]]''', and '''[[Nekhen]]''' dominate [[Upper Egypt]].\n|-\n|The [[city-state]]s of '''[[Eridu]]''', '''[[Bad-tibira]]''', '''[[Larsa]]''', '''[[Sippar]]''', and '''[[Shuruppak]]''' rise to prominence in [[Sumer]].\n|}\n\n===Tenth Millennium BCE===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:5%\"|Year||style=\"width:95%\"|Event\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;9000&nbsp;BCE||First stone structures at '''[[Jericho]]''' are built.\n|-\n|align=center|about&nbsp;9500&nbsp;BCE||Building begins at '''[[G\u00f6bekli Tepe]]'''.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Lists of capitals}}\n*[[List of sovereign states by date of formation]]\n*[[List of former sovereign states]]\n*[[commons:Category:Blank maps of the world for historical use|Blank maps of the world for historical use]]\n*[[List of administrative division name changes]]\n*[[List of city name changes]]\n*[[List of national border changes since World War I]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links|country}}\n{{Wikidata property|P17}}\n\n{{Lists of countries and territories by continent}}\n{{Territorial evolution of the world}}\n\n[[Category:Geography-related lists]]\n[[Category:Geopolitics]]\n[[Category:History-related lists]]\n[[Category:Maps]]\n[[Category:National histories| ]]\n[[Category:Territorial evolution| ]]\n[[Category:Timelines by country| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{split|Timeline of historical geopolitical changes (21st century)|Timeline of historical geopolitical changes (20th century)|Timeline of historical geopolitical changes (19th century)|Timeline of historical geopolitical changes (18th century)|Timeline of historical geopolitical changes (pre-18th century)|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n<!-- Please put all entries in present tense. -->\n{{cleanup|date=January 2019|reason=sections and lists in reverse chronological order, contrary to [[WP:DATELIST]]}}\nThis is a '''timeline of country and capital changes''' around the world. It includes dates of [[declarations of independence]], [[geographical renaming|changes in country name]], changes of [[capital city]] or name, and significant [[Political history of the world|changes in territory]] such as the [[annexation]], [[cession]], or [[secession]] of land.\n\nThe types of changes listed here usually include (but are not limited to) the alteration of borders, the creation and fall of [[State (polity)|states]], changes of geographical names, as well as a few geographical changes caused by unusually destructive natural disasters. Through the knowledge of such dates and events, the approximate year and age of a [[world map]] could be calculated and estimated.\n\nNot all maps of the world created during a given age or period will be the same across the globe, as different [[cartography|mapmakers]]{{spnd}}or their employers{{spnd}}may have different views on the sovereignty or territorial integrity of the countries of the world or possess different levels of technological sophistication or geographical insight. {{citation needed span|Even maps created by the same mapmaker around the same time can differ significantly.|date=January 2019|reason=This statement needs not just a reference to two maps, but rather a WP:SECONDARY source that supports this assertion.}}\n\nThe timeline below presents its information in reverse chronological order, beginning in the modern era and working backwards.\n\nThis article uses the [[Common Era|Common Calendar System]], which was established as the new [[Gregorian calendar|Christian Calendar]] by [[Pope Gregory XIII]] in 1582. The Common Calendar uses the designation [[Common Era]] (CE or AD for [[Anno Domini]]) for years starting 1 January 1&nbsp;CE, and [[Before Common Era]] (BCE or BC for [[Before Christ]]) for years before that date. The Common Calendar also follows the [[ordinal number]]s rather than the [[cardinal number]]s, so there was no \"[[year zero]]\" in this format; that is, the date 1 January 1&nbsp;CE immediately followed the date 31 December 1&nbsp;BCE. For the same reason, while the [[Year 2000 problem|2000s]] began on Saturday, 1 January 2000&nbsp;CE, the official [[3rd millennium|Third Millennium]] began on Monday, 1 January 2001&nbsp;CE.\n\n{{center|\n'''&nbsp;[[#21st century|2000s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#1990s|1900s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#1890s|1800s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#18th century|1700s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#17th century|1600s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#16th century|1500s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#15th century|1400s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#14th century|1300s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#13th century|1200s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#12th century|1100s]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#11th century|1000s]]&nbsp;<br/>&nbsp;[[#1990s|1st&nbsp;Millennium&nbsp;CE]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#First Millennium&nbsp;BCE|1st&nbsp;Millennium&nbsp;BCE]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#Second Millennium&nbsp;BCE|2nd&nbsp;Millennium&nbsp;BCE]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#Third Millennium&nbsp;BCE|3rd&nbsp;Millennium&nbsp;BCE]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#Fourth Millennium&nbsp;BCE|4th&nbsp;Millennium&nbsp;BCE]]&nbsp; &nbsp;[[#Tenth Millennium&nbsp;BCE|10th&nbsp;Millennium&nbsp;BCE]]&nbsp;'''\n}}\n\n{{Expand list|date=November 2019}}\n\n===21st century===\n\n====2010s====\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:6%\"|Year||style=\"width:8%\"|Date||style=\"width:86%\"|Event\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n|align=center|20&nbsp;March||'''[[Kazakhstan]]''' changes the name of its capital from Astana to [[Nur-Sultan]] in honour of ex-President [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]] after the [[Constitution of Kazakhstan]] is amended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meduza.io/news/2019/03/20/parlament-kazahstana-odobril-pereimenovanie-astany-v-nursultan|title=Parliament of Kazakhstan approves renaming of Astana to Nursultan|last=|first=|date=|website=meduza.io|language=Russian|access-date=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=center|12&nbsp;February||The [[Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia]] adopts the name '''[[Republic of North Macedonia]]''' as part of the [[Prespa agreement]], under which [[Greece]] will no longer veto the country's accession to [[NATO]] and the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vlada.mk/node/16763?ln=en-gb|title=Announcement of the Government of the Republic of North Macedonia for entry into force of the Final Agreement, Constitutional Amendments and Constitutional Law for Implementation of Amendments |work=Government of the Republic of North Macedonia |date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213025155/https://vlada.mk/node/16763?ln=en-gb |archive-date=13 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"TestoridesPaphitis2019\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/macedonia-vote-rattles-government-in-neighbor-greece/2019/01/11/5d31e88e-15a4-11e9-ab79-30cd4f7926f2_story.html |title=Europe: Macedonian lawmakers set to vote to change country's name |work=The Washington Post |date=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113162131/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/macedonia-vote-rattles-government-in-neighbor-greece/2019/01/11/5d31e88e-15a4-11e9-ab79-30cd4f7926f2_story.html |archive-date=13 January 2019 |url-status=live |first=Konstantin |last=Testorides |author1-link=Konstantin Testorides |first2=Nicholas |last2=Paphitis |author2-link=Nicholas Paphitis |agency=Associated Press |quote=Macedonia late Friday {{bracket|11 January 2019}} fulfilled its part of a historic deal that will pave its way to NATO membership and normalize relations with neighboring Greece, after lawmakers approved constitutional changes to rename the country North Macedonia.&nbsp;... {{bracket|Under}} the full implementation of the agreement&nbsp;... Greece will lift its objections to Macedonia joining NATO and the EU.}}</ref> [[Skopje]] remains the capital.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n| align=center|24&nbsp;December||'''[[Burundi]]''' moves its capital from [[Bujumbura]] to [[Gitega]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-12-24/burundi-moves-political-capital-from-bujumbura-to-gitega|title=Burundi Moves Political Capital From Bujumbura to Gitega|date=24 December 2018|access-date=27 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227084940/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-12-24/burundi-moves-political-capital-from-bujumbura-to-gitega|archive-date=27 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|9&nbsp;July||'''[[Ethiopia]]''' ends its occupation of [[Badme]] and returns the town to '''[[Eritrea]]''' following a [[2018 Eritrea\u2013Ethiopia summit|peace summit]], ending their 20-year [[Eritrean\u2013Ethiopian border conflict|border conflict]].\n|-\n| align=center|19&nbsp;April||The [[Swaziland|Kingdom of Swaziland]] changes its name to the '''[[Eswatini|Kingdom of Eswatini]]'''. [[Mbabane]] remains the capital.<ref>{{cite web |title=The World Factbook - What's New |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/docs/whatsnew.html |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |accessdate=11 June 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611064949/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/docs/whatsnew.html |archivedate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|2&nbsp;February||The [[International Court of Justice|International Court of Justice (ICJ)]] rules that a strip of northern [[Isla Calero|Isla Portillos]] at the mouth of the [[San Juan River (Nicaragua)|San Juan River]] in '''[[Nicaragua]]''' belongs to '''[[Costa Rica]]'''.<ref>{{cite web|title = Map: Costa Rica & Nicaragua Settle Border Dispute in Court.|date = 3 February 2018|website = Polgeonow.com|url = http://www.polgeonow.com/2018/02/nicaragua-costa-rica-border-dispute-ruling-icj-2018.html|access-date = 4 February 2018|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072738/http://www.polgeonow.com/2018/02/nicaragua-costa-rica-border-dispute-ruling-icj-2018.html|archive-date = 5 February 2018|url-status = live|df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center|1&nbsp;January||'''[[Belgium]]''' and '''[[The Netherlands]]''' finalize an exchange of territory along the [[Meuse River]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Staudenmaier|first=Rebecca|title=Belgium And Netherlands Swap Land In The New Year|date=1 January 2018|website=[[Deutsche Welle]]|url=http://www.dw.com/en/belgium-and-netherlands-swap-land-in-the-new-year/a-41988494|access-date=1 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103000700/http://www.dw.com/en/belgium-and-netherlands-swap-land-in-the-new-year/a-41988494|archive-date=3 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The agreement, initially signed on 28 November 2016, involves a one-for-two swap of three tiny islands, with the Netherlands gaining {{convert|24.7|acres|ha}} of land near [[Oost-Maarland]], so that [[enclaves and exclaves|pene-exclaves]] caused by the straightening of the Meuse can be fixed. Presqu'ile de L'llal and Presqu'ile d'Eijsden, which were formerly Belgian, were swapped for a former Dutch piece of land, Presqu'ile Petit-Gravier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/11/28/Netherlands-to-grow-247-acres-in-land-swap-with-Belgium/9481480343727/|title=Netherlands to grow 24.7 acres in land swap with Belgium|website=[[UPI]]|last=Cone|first=Allen|date=28 November 2016|access-date=21 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022032632/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2016/11/28/Netherlands-to-grow-247-acres-in-land-swap-with-Belgium/9481480343727/|archive-date=22 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"4\"|2017\n|align=center|24&nbsp;June||[[Egypt]] transfers sovereignty of [[Sanafir Island]] and [[Tiran Island]] to [[Saudi Arabia]].\n|-\n|align=center|9&nbsp;April||Following a [[South Ossetian name change referendum, 2017|referendum]], the [[South Ossetia|Republic of South Ossetia]] changes its name to the '''[[South Ossetia|Republic of South Ossetia \u2013 the State of Alania]]'''.\n|-\n|align=center|21&nbsp;February||Th