f Pontus|Pontus]] and create a client state out of the Eastern portion under [[Pharnaces II of Pontus|Pharnaces II]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[111&nbsp;BCE]]||||By this date, the [[Han dynasty]] under [[Emperor Wu of Han|Wu]] had conquered much of what is today Southern China and Northern Vietnam from [[Nanyue]]. Start of the [[First Chinese domination of Vietnam]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[133&nbsp;BCE]]||||Upon the death of [[Attalus III]], he wills his kingdom of [[Pergamon]] to the [[Roman Republic]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[133&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer Celtiberia following the Siege of Numantia\n|-\n|align=center|[[135&nbsp;BCE]]||||Western half of [[Minyue]] conquered by the [[Han dynasty]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberia]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Ancient Carthage]] is disestablished\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans conquer [[Corinth]] and dissolve the [[Achaean League]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[146&nbsp;BCE]]||||Roman provinces of [[Macedonia (Roman province)|Macedon]] and [[Achaea (Roman province)|Achaea]] formed\n|-\n|align=center|[[148&nbsp;BCE]]||||Mithridates I of Parthia conquers Ectebana\n|-\n|align=center|[[168&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans dissolve the Kingdom of Macedon after the Battle of Pydna.\n|-\n|align=center|[[180&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Demetrius I of Bactria]] invades India, forming the [[Indo-Greek Kingdom]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[187&nbsp;BCE]]||||The [[Shunga Empire]] is formed after the [[Mauryan Empire]] is destroyed\n|-\n|align=center|[[194&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Wanggeom-seong]] becomes the capital of '''[[Wiman Joseon]]''' on the [[Korean Peninsula]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[194&nbsp;BCE]]||||Seleucids take control of Coele Syria and Judea from Ptolemaic Egypt\n|-\n|align=center|[[194&nbsp;BCE]]||||Romans force Philip of Macedon to abandon Greece in the Peace of Flamininus, while allowing him to maintain Macedon itself.\n|-\n|align=center|[[202&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|28&nbsp;February||[[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Gaozu]] establishes the '''[[Han dynasty#Western Han|Western Han dynasty]] in [[China]]'''. [[Chang'an]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[204&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Zhao Tuo|Wu]] establishes '''[[Nanyue]]''' in what is now Southern China. [[Panyu District|Panyu]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[209&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||The Romans conquer Cartagena from the Carthaginians, bringing Carthaginian Spain under Roman control\n|-\n|align=center|[[211&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||Romans capture [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[221&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Qin Shi Huang]] unifies [[History of China#Qin dynasty (221-206 BCE)|ancient China]] and establishes the '''[[Qin dynasty]] in [[China]]'''. [[Xianyang]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[230&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Han (state)|Han]] conquered by [[Qin (state)|Qin]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[238&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Arsaces I of Parthia]] establishes the '''[[Arsacid Dynasty of Parthia]]'''. [[Hecatompylus]] becomes the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[238&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Sardinia]] and [[Corsica]] become Roman provinces\n|-\n|align=center|[[238&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Sicily]] becomes first Roman province\n|-\n|align=center|[[266&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Ashoka]] unifies most of South Asia\n|-\n|align=center|[[281&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Lysimachus]] dies at the [[Battle of Corupedium]], his empire falling to the [[Seleucid Empire|Seleucids]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[291&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius Poliorcetes]] captures Thebes after a successful [[Siege of Thebes (292\u2013291 BC)|siege]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[294&nbsp;BCE]]||||Demetrius I of Macedon kills [[Alexander V of Macedon]], and in claiming the throne loses [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]] to a revolt.\n|-\n|align=center|[[301&nbsp;BCE]]||||The death of [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus]] at the [[Battle of Ipsus]] results in his kingdom being divided between the remaining [[Diadochi]], namely [[Ptolemy I Soter]], [[Seleucus I Nicator]], [[Lysimachus]], and [[Cassander]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[305&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Macedon]]ian general [[Ptolemy I Soter|Ptolemy]] establishes the '''[[Ptolemaic Dynasty of Egypt]]''' as King [[Ptolemy I Soter]]. [[Alexandria]] remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[306&nbsp;BCE]]||||Following the death of [[Alexander IV of Macedon]], [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus]] declares himself an independent king, soon to by followed by his fellow Diadochi [[Ptolemy I Soter]], [[Seleucus I Nicator]], [[Lysimachus]], and [[Cassander]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[309&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Seleucus I Nicator]] forms the [[Seleucid Empire]] after conquering Babylonia, Media, and Elam from [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus]] in the [[Babylonian War]], leaving him with one third of his empire.\n|-\n|align=center|[[312&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Macedon]]ian general [[Seleucus I Nicator|Seleucus]] establishes the '''[[Seleucid Empire]]'''. [[Babylon]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[316&nbsp;BCE]]||||The states of [[Shu (state)|Shu]] and [[Ba (state)|Ba]] are conquered by [[King Huiwen of Qin]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[322&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Chandragupta Maurya|Chandragupta]] establishes the '''[[Maurya Empire]]''' of [[History of India#Maurya dynasty|ancient India]]. [[Pataliputra]] (now [[Patna]]) is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[323&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Alexander the Great|Alexander]] dies and his empire splits\n|-\n|align=center|[[329&nbsp;BCE]]||||Alexander conquers [[Samarkand]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[330&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Alexander the Great]] of [[Macedon]] conquers '''[[Persia]]'''. Alexander makes [[Babylon]] the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[332&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Alexander the Great]] of [[Macedon]] conquers [[Achaemenid Empire|Persian-occupied]] [[History of Ptolemaic Egypt|Egypt]] and establishes the '''[[Argead dynasty|Argead Dynasty of Egypt]]''' as [[Pharaoh]] [[Alexander the Great|Alexander III]]. Alexander builds a new capital at [[Alexandria]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[338&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Phillip II of Macedon]] unites Greece\n|-\n|align=center|[[343&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Artaxerxes III of Persia]] reconquers [[Egypt]] and establishes the [[Achaemenid Empire|Persian]] '''[[Thirty-first Dynasty of Egypt]]''' as [[Pharaoh]] [[Artaxerxes III of Persia|Artaxerxes III]]. \n|-\n|align=center|[[375&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||[[Zheng (state)|Zheng]] annexed by [[Han (state)|Han]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[380&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|November||[[Pharaoh]] [[Nectanebo I]] establishes the '''[[Thirtieth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Sebennytos]] becomes the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[387&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||The [[Peace of Antalcidas]] imposes Persian rule on the Greek cities of Asia and Cyprus.\n|-\n|align=center|[[399&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|autumn||[[Pharaoh]] [[Nefaarud I]] establishes the '''[[Twenty-ninth Dynasty of Egypt]]'''. [[Mendes]] becomes the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[404&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Amyrtaeus]] expels the [[Achaemenid Empire|Persians]] from [[Egypt]] and establishes the '''[[Twenty-eighth Dynasty of Egypt]]''' as [[Pharaoh]] [[Amyrtaeus]]. [[Sais]] is the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[404&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Athens]] surrenders to [[Sparta]] and her allies, resulting in the dismemberment of the Delian League and a temporary Spartan hegemony\n|-\n|align=center|[[405&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Gela]] and [[Camarina]] in Sicily are abandoned by the Greeks and sacked by [[Carthage]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[406&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Agrigento|Akragas]] in Sicily is abandoned by the Greeks and sacked by Carthage\n|-\n|align=center|[[409&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Selinus]] and [[Himera]] in Sicily are destroyed by Carthage\n|-\n|align=center|[[479&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Delian League]] established\n|-\n|align=center|[[504&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[King]] [[Panduvasudeva]] moves the capital of the '''[[Kingdom of Lanka]]''' to [[Upatissa Nuwara]]. \n|-\n|align=center|[[509&nbsp;BCE]]||||The '''[[Roman Republic]]''' supersedes the [[King of Rome|Kingdom of Rome]]. The city of Rome remains the capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[515&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Darius the Great]] moves the capital of the '''[[Achaemenid Empire|Persian Empire]]''' to [[Persepolis]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[525&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|May||[[Cambyses II of Persia]] conquers [[Egypt]] and establishes the [[Achaemenid Empire|Persian]] '''[[Twenty-seventh Dynasty of Egypt]]''' as [[Pharaoh]] [[Cambyses II of Persia|Cambyses II]]. \n|-\n|align=center|[[535&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||[[Cyrus the Great]] conquers the [[Gandhara Kingdom]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[539&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center| ||[[Cyrus the Great]] conquers the [[Neo-Babylonian Empire]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[543&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[King]] [[Vijaya of Sri Lanka|Vijaya]] establishes the '''[[Kingdom of Lanka]]''' and makes [[Tambapanni]] the new capital. \n|-\n|align=center|[[546&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Cyrus the Great]] conquers the [[Lydia|Lydian Empire]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[546&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Cyrus the Great]] establishes the '''[[Achaemenid Empire|Persian Empire]]''' and makes [[Pasargadae]] the new capital.\n|-\n|align=center|[[586&nbsp;BCE]]||||Traditional date for the destruction of the [[Kingdom of Judah]] at the hands of the Babylonians.\n|-\n|align=center|[[605&nbsp;BCE]]||||With the [[Battle of Carchemish]], the Assyrian Empire is destroyed and replaced by a balance of power between [[Babylon]], [[Medes|Media]], [[Lydia]] and [[Ancient Egypt|Egypt]].\n|-\n|align=center|[[609&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Harran]], the new capital of Assyria, is destroyed by the Medes and Babylonians\n|-\n|align=center|[[612&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Nineveh]] falls to a coalition of the Medes and Babylonians\n|-\n|align=center|[[650&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Ancient Carthage]] is established\n|-\n|align=center|[[653&nbsp;BCE]]||||After the [[Battle of Ulai]], [[Elam]] is vassalized by the Assyrians\n|-\n|align=center|[[657&nbsp;BCE]]||||[[Byzantium]] is settled by colonists from [[Megara]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[660&nbsp;BCE]]||align=center|11&nbsp;February||[[Emperor Jimmu]] establishes the '''[[History of Japan|Empire of Japan]]'''.\n|-\n| style